281.5	Lewis_Carroll	Lewis Carroll	Charles Lutwidge Dodgson ( -wij -sən; 27 January 1832 – 14 January 1898), better known by the pseudonym Lewis Carroll ( -əl), was an English author, mathematician, logician, Anglican deacon and photographer. His most famous writings are Alice's Adventures in Wonderland and its sequel Through the Looking-Glass, as well as the poems "The Hunting of the Snark" and "Jabberwocky", all examples of the genre of literary nonsense. He is noted for his facility at word play, logic, and fantasy, and there are societies dedicated to the enjoyment and promotion of his works and the investigation of his life in many parts of the world, including the United Kingdom, Japan, the United States, and New Zealand.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/LewisCarrollSelfPhoto.jpg/220px-LewisCarrollSelfPhoto.jpg
